ns**\\\\n\\\\nI’m dealing with a tiny library and need to test the cbor default and registration. I think I might build on the serialization compiler with @Serializable and Ktor server/client. The cbor function is tied to Configuration, and I could create a fake Configuration to capture registering arguments. Also, maybe I can use KotlinxSerializationConverter to serialize and deserialize maps/lists with cbor. However, I need to ensure compliance with the user's requirement of no direct reflection or conventional serialization, which feels tricky since it’s a serialization library.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Clarifying serialization options**\\\\n\\\\nI think they’re suggesting no direct reflection or Java serialization, which is a bit ambiguous. I need to test the serialization library using the public API and avoid direct reflection. I might not be able to use the @Serializable plugin with built-in serializers effectively. Using Map<String, List<Int>> could help, but I wonder about the TypeInfo with reified KType. It seems the Ktor KotlinxSerializationConverter handles serialization, and I’ll have to inspect how the converter behaves with the mentioned content types.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Testing converter functionality**\\\\n\\\\nI realize that I’m testing the converter here, not the cbor extension itself. The cbor extension actually registers through a serialization helper. It’s important to keep that distinction in mind, as I focus on how the converter behaves during this process. I need to ensure that I’m accurately assessing the converter’s functionality without getting muddled with the cbor extension’s registration process. That clarity will help me make the most of my testing efforts.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating test requirements**\\\\n\\\\nI might need to test the library meaningfully, but the instructions say to only modify the test file. It seem